What is R?

R is a statistical computing and graphics system. This system is comprised of two parts: the R language itself and a run-time environment.

Open Source: R is an open-source language, which means its freely available for anyone to use, modify, and distribute.

Customization: R simplifies data manipulation tasks and allows for extensive customization of plots and analyses, giving users the flexibility to tailor their work to specific research needs.

Integration: R can be easily integrated with other programming languages like Python, SQL, and C++.

Reproducibility: R encourages reproducible research through tools like RMarkdown, making it easy to create dynamic documents that combine code, results, and explanations.

Windows users: CTRL + Enter

MacOS users: Command + Enter ( + Enter)

Assignment operator

x <- 125
print(x)
## [1] 125

In R, the <- operator is used for assignment. When you use it as shown in your statement, it assigns a value to an object (variable) if that object already exists. If the object doesnt exist, R will create it and assign the specified value to it. Sometimes, = is used instead <- but be careful not to confuse this sign with the equals sign ==.

Keyboard shortcuts for <-

  • Windows users: Alt +
  • macOS: Option +

Understanding object classes

Simple functions

result <- sqrt(x = 16)
result
## [1] 4

sqrt() - square root function. sqrt is the name of the function, and within (), you specify the arguments to which the function with this name will be applied.

x - denotes the functions argument (in different functions, arguments can have different names).

4 - the value we pass as an argument to the function (to which the function will be applied).

<- - assignment operator

result - an object in which we store the result of the functions execution. The names of objects can be different (its better to follow a style guide for naming).

Can you write a function of squaring of 7?

result2 <- 7^2

Variables

  • numerical (discrete, continuous)

  • categorical (nominal, ordinal)

  • logical (or boolean)

my_numeric <- 42.5

my_character <- "some text"

my_logical <- TRUE

Variable types can be changed

my_numeric <- as.character(my_numeric)
class(my_numeric)
## [1] "character"
# see also: as.numeric, as.factor, as.logical, as.Date

Vectors

  • ordered sequence of values of the same data type. It can contain numeric values, characters, logical values (TRUE/FALSE), or other data types, as long as all elements in the vector are of the same type:
numeric_vector <- c(1, 10, 49)
character_vector <- c("a", "b", "c")

# changing vector
names(numeric_vector) <- c("Marcelo", "Angela", "Widodo")
numeric_vector
## Marcelo  Angela  Widodo 
##       1      10      49
  • mathematical operations with vectors
# Summing up votes for political parties
party_votes_2020 <- c(59500, 30100, 18780, 12900)
total_votes_2020 <- sum(party_votes_2020)
total_votes_2020
## [1] 121280
# Distributing seats to each party proportional to their share of the total vote
seats_available <- 17
seat_distribution <- party_votes_2020 / sum(party_votes_2020) * seats_available
seat_distribution
## [1] 8.340204 4.219162 2.632421 1.808212
  • create another vector for parties results in 2015, then create a vector vote_change based on the difference in values for different years
party_votes_2015 <- c(46070, 29000, 17035, 18000)
vote_change <- party_votes_2020 - party_votes_2015
vote_change
## [1] 13430  1100  1745 -5100

Matrices

  • a set of elements of the same data type (numeric, character/categorical, or boolean) arranged in a fixed number of rows and columns:
m <- matrix(1:9, byrow = TRUE, nrow = 3)
m
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    2    3
## [2,]    4    5    6
## [3,]    7    8    9
# The byrow argument specifies that the matrix is filled with values row by row. If we want the values in the matrix to be filled by columns, we simply place byrow = FALSE

# Rows and columns can be named: rownames(my_matrix) <- row_names_vector; colnames(my_matrix) <- col_names_vector

rownames(m) <- c("Party A", "Party B", "Party C")
m
##         [,1] [,2] [,3]
## Party A    1    2    3
## Party B    4    5    6
## Party C    7    8    9
colnames(m) <- c("2010", "2015", "2020")
m
##         2010 2015 2020
## Party A    1    2    3
## Party B    4    5    6
## Party C    7    8    9
# Summation
rowSums(m)
## Party A Party B Party C 
##       6      15      24
colSums(m)
## 2010 2015 2020 
##   12   15   18

Reproduce this text matrix:

matrix_text <- matrix(c("True positive", "False positive", "False negative", "True negative"), nrow = 2, byrow = TRUE)

Lists

  • while matrices hold only one data type (numeric, character, etc.), lists can hold elements of different data types, including vectors, matrices, data frames, other lists, and even functions;

  • lists have a flexible structure, and each element can have its own name or be accessed by indexing:

election_results <- list(
  PartyVotes = party_votes_2020,
  SeatDistribution = seat_distribution,
  DeputiesAge = matrix(c(56, 61, 59, 49), nrow = 2)
)
election_results
## $PartyVotes
## [1] 59500 30100 18780 12900
## 
## $SeatDistribution
## [1] 8.340204 4.219162 2.632421 1.808212
## 
## $DeputiesAge
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]   56   59
## [2,]   61   49

Data frames

  • two-dimensional data structure that can combine any types of variables at the same time;
  • each column in a data frame represents a variable, and each row represents an observation:
protest_data <- data.frame(
  Date = as.Date(c("2023-08-10", "2023-08-15", "2023-08-20", "2023-08-12")),
  City = c("Berlin", "Strasbourg", "Bologna", "Madrid"),
  Event = c("Protest for Equality", "Environmental Rally", "Labor Strike", "Anti-Corruption Protest"),
  Temperature_Celsius = c(26, 30, 39, 32),
  Participants = c(250, 85, 320, 140)
)
  • Can you write a missing value in one of the variables? mydata$variable[raws number] <- NA
protest_data$Participants[2] <- NA

Data frames with data.table

protest_data <- data.table(
  Date = as.Date(c("2023-08-10", "2023-08-15", "2023-08-20", "2023-08-12")),
  City = c("Berlin", "Strasbourg", "Bologna", "Madrid"),
  Event = c("Protest for Equality", "Environmental Rally", "Labor Strike", "Anti-Corruption Protest"),
  Temperature_Celsius = c(26, 30, 39, 32),
  Participants = c(250, 85, 320, 140)
)

Subsetting Rows and Columns

You can easily subset rows and columns using data.table syntax:

  • Subset rows based on conditions:
protest_data[City == "Berlin"]
##          Date   City                Event Temperature_Celsius Participants
## 1: 2023-08-10 Berlin Protest for Equality                  26          250
# Can you write a new object 'subset_raws'?
  • Subset specific columns:
protest_data[, .(Date, City, Event)]
##          Date       City                   Event
## 1: 2023-08-10     Berlin    Protest for Equality
## 2: 2023-08-15 Strasbourg     Environmental Rally
## 3: 2023-08-20    Bologna            Labor Strike
## 4: 2023-08-12     Madrid Anti-Corruption Protest

Sorting Data

Sort data by one or more columns:

protest_data[order(Date)]
##          Date       City                   Event Temperature_Celsius
## 1: 2023-08-10     Berlin    Protest for Equality                  26
## 2: 2023-08-12     Madrid Anti-Corruption Protest                  32
## 3: 2023-08-15 Strasbourg     Environmental Rally                  30
## 4: 2023-08-20    Bologna            Labor Strike                  39
##    Participants
## 1:          250
## 2:          140
## 3:           85
## 4:          320

Aggregating Data

Perform aggregations on data:

  • Calculate mean temperature:
protest_data[, .(Mean_Temperature = mean(Temperature_Celsius))]
##    Mean_Temperature
## 1:            31.75
# Create a new object 'mean_temp'
  • Group by City and calculate mean participants:
protest_data[, .(Mean_Participants = mean(Participants)), by = City]
##          City Mean_Participants
## 1:     Berlin               250
## 2: Strasbourg                85
## 3:    Bologna               320
## 4:     Madrid               140

Data Table Operations

  • Add a new column:
protest_data[, Arrested := "0"]
  • Remove a column:
protest_data[, Arrested := NULL]
  • Can you add a raw? TIP: function rbind
new_row <- data.table(
  Date = as.Date("2023-08-25"),
  City = "Paris",
  Event = "Human Rights March",
  Temperature_Celsius = 28,
  Participants = 200
)

protest_data <- rbind(protest_data, new_row)
  • Can you remove it?
protest_data <- protest_data[-5, ]

Reproducible workflow

it is an approach in data science where every step of a project is documented and organized in such a way that others (or your future yourself) can reproduce the results exactly.

Setting up working directory

  • check current location of your directory
getwd()
## [1] "C:/Program Files/GitHub/IntroR/Session1"
  • you can change the working directory using the setwd() command (set working directory):
setwd()

More: https://statisticsglobe.com/function-create-directory-file-path-r

R Project

If you are working on a single project, such as a prospectus, you can create a separate folder and a dedicated project directory that contains your R scripts, data, and other project-related files. In this case, you do not need to set a new directory, by default it will refer to the folder where you created the project.

Use File > New Project

More details: https://support.posit.co/hc/en-us/articles/200526207-Using-RStudio-Projects

Some typical errors

Some typical errors

Unmatched parentheses, curly braces, square brackets or quotes

mean(c(1, 7, 13)
sex_vector <- c("Male","Female","Female",Male")
factor_sex_vector == as.factor(sex_vector)
install.packages(MASS)

Wrong, inappropriate or inconsistent data types

gender <- factor(c("female", "female", "male", "female", "male"))
mean(gender)
y <- c(2.4, 3.7, 5.1, "9.8")
class(y)

Missing, incorrect or misspelled arguments in functions

rnorm(n = 3, var = 1) # use ?help for getting information about this function
mean(c(1, 7, 13, NA), narm = TRUE)

More: https://statsandr.com/blog/top-10-errors-in-r/
